	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Most Game Boy games blank the screen as soon as they get control of the CPU. Wordtris, on the other hand, scrolls the Nintendo logo off the bottom. So if you start Wordtris on a Super Game Boy, you see the Super Game Boy intro, and then you catch a glimpse of the Game Boy's Nintendo logo before it falls out of view. Want me to put a video of this on YouTube if I can find my equipment?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>byuu</b> [ Mon Sep 28, 2009 10:59 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">caitsith2 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Not only that, this boot rom does NOT validate the logo NOR the header.<br /><br />It is the snes that does that.  If the snes side bios was to be patched to always run,  then any logo could be used there.</div>
<br />
<br />That is correct. What's interesting is that the logo data is displayed no matter what, but the SNES BIOS only proceeds to play the game when the bootup code matches what's cached inside the BIOS.
<br />
<br />The main thing this 256-byte boot ROM does is send six packet commands to the SGB BIOS which contain the bootup code.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


